Spatial footprint of larval restoration

2023-10-02

The output of coralseed can (settlement points and particle paths) be used to quantify summary statistics for spatial patterns, allowing for comparisons between sites or between tidal cycles/days/years. Some key questions that stem from larval restoration include:

  1. What proportion of larvae settled from the initial reseeding number?

  2. How long on average did it take for larvae to settle? (time in minutes)

  3. How far did larvae travel before settling? (distance in metres)

  4. Over what area did the larvae settle? (i.e. what is the restoration footprint in km2?)

  5. What is the mean density of settlers? (individuals per 20m2)

  6. What is the maximum density of settlers? (individuals per 20m2)

  7. What is the mean distance between settlers? (distance in metres)

  8. How clustered are the larvae in space? (nearest neighbour index - Clark Evans index)

  9. How dispersed are the larvae? (sum of squared distances around the mean)

Below is an example run with a realistic number of larvae for reseeding: 1 million larvae. The code uses the mermaid bay example of 1000 particle tracks and iterates 1000 times across the particle tracks to generate variance from the coralseed model. In practice this can be any number of simulations for any number of tracks depending on the compute time (warning: 1e-06 particles takes up compute time, see tic() toc() times inset in the code from an M2 Max processor)

  • 1,000,000 larvae = 8.2 minutes (~350MB RDS file)
  • 10,000,000 larvae = 80.2 minutes (3.37GB RDS file)
library(tidyverse)
library(doParallel)
library(foreach)
library(sf)
library(coralseed)
library(tictoc)

# first set spatial mosaic of habitat preference via coralseed
seascape <- coralseed::seascape_probability(reefoutline = reef_map, habitat=benthic_map)

nsims_footprint <- 1000
ncores <- detectCores()
cl <- makeCluster(ncores-1, port=12345)
registerDoParallel(cl)

#tic()
output_footprint <- foreach(i = 1:nsims_footprint, .packages = "coralseed") %dopar% seed_futures(
  example="mermaid", input=NULL,  seascape = seascape, tracks = TRUE, set.seed=NULL, silent = TRUE, 
  competency.function = "exponential", limit.time = 6.95, probability = "additive",
  simulate.mortality = "typeI", simulate.mortality.n = 0.1
)

#  the `seed_futures` function outputs paths and points needed for analysis in a single object, so use `extract_parallel` to separate them out as individual objects:
output_points <- extract_parallel(type = "points", output_footprint)
output_paths <- extract_parallel(type = "paths", output_footprint)

#toc()
#saveRDS(output_footprint, "output_footprint.rds")

stopCluster(cl)

As output of seed_futures (via settle_particles) is an sf format, then the output can be converted to ppp format using spatstat.geom::as.ppp(sf::st_as_sf(outputfile)) and leverage the extensive spatstat package for quantifying spatial point patterns (nndist and nni are included below as examples). Below are examples of how to interpret the output of coral_seed models:


1) Settlement success

Total number of larvae settled:

paste0(nrow(output_points), " / 1,000,000 larvae settled")
## [1] "126836 / 1,000,000 larvae settled"

What percent of released larvae settled?

summary.proportion <- output_points |>
  group_by(id) |>
  dplyr::summarise(proportion = n() / 1000 * 100)

summary.proportion <- summary.proportion$proportion
df_meanproportion <- data.frame(values = summary.proportion, factor = "meantimetosettlement")
paste0(round(mean(summary.proportion),1), "% settlement")
## [1] "13% settlement"


2) Time to settlement:

How long on average do larvae take to settle?

settlement.time <- output_points |>
  group_by(id) |>
  summarise(disp = mean(dispersaltime))
settlement.time <- settlement.time$disp
df_meantime <- data.frame(values = settlement.time, factor = "meantimetosettlement")
paste0(round(mean(settlement.time)/60,1), " hours")
## [1] "3.6 hours"


3) Larval distance

How far on average did larvae travel before settling?

# mean dispersal length per iter
summary.dispersaldistances <- sapply(split(
  output_paths,
  output_paths$id
), function(sub_df) { # Applying function over each split
  mean(sf::st_length(sub_df$geometry)) / 1000
})
df_meandistance <- data.frame(values = summary.dispersaldistances, factor = "meandistancetosettlement")
paste0(round(mean(summary.dispersaldistances),2), " kilometres")
## [1] "0.14 kilometres"


4) Dispersal footprint

Over what area did larvae disperse? (i.e. what is the total restoration footprint?)

summary.dispersal.area <- sapply(split(
  output_points,
  output_points$id
), function(sub_df) { # Applying function over each split
  st_area(settlement_statistics(sub_df, cellsize = 20)$area)
})
df_footprint <- data.frame(values = summary.dispersal.area, factor = "spatialfootprint")

paste0(round(mean(summary.dispersal.area)*0.0001,2), " ha")
## [1] "0.55 ha"


5) Settlement density

What is the mean count of settlers (per 20m2)?

summary.dispersal.mean.count <- sapply(split(
  output_points,
  output_points$id
), function(sub_df) { # Applying function over each split
  tmp <- (settlement_statistics(sub_df, cellsize = 20)$grid)
  tmp$count[is.na(tmp$count)] <- 0
  mean(tmp$count)
})
df_meandensity <- data.frame(values = summary.dispersal.mean.count, factor = "meandensity")
paste0(round(mean(summary.dispersal.mean.count)/20,2), " settlers per m2")
## [1] "0.12 settlers per m2"

what is the maximum count of settlers (per 20m2)?

summary.dispersal.max.count <- sapply(split(
  output_points,
  output_points$id
), function(sub_df) { # Applying function over each split
  tmp <- (settlement_statistics(sub_df, cellsize = 20)$grid)
  tmp$count[is.na(tmp$count)] <- 0
  max(tmp$count)
})
df_maxdensity <- data.frame(values = summary.dispersal.max.count, factor = "maxdensity")
paste0(round(mean(summary.dispersal.max.count)/20,2), " settlers per m2")
## [1] "1.46 settlers per m2"


7) Spatial patterns

How clustered are the larvae?

Nearest-neighbour distance (distance to nearest neighbour)

summary.nnd <- sapply(split(output_points, output_points$id), function(sub_df) { # Applying function over each split
  mean(spatstat.geom::nndist(spatstat.geom::as.ppp(st_as_sf(select(sub_df, id))))) # nnd
})
df_nnd <- data.frame(values = summary.nnd, factor = "nnd")
paste0(round(mean(summary.nnd),2), " metres")
## [1] "2.6 metres"

Clark-Evans Index:

summary.nni <- sapply(split(output_points, output_points$id), function(sub_df) { # Applying function over each split
  points_ppp <- spatstat.geom::as.ppp(st_as_sf(select(sub_df, id))) # nnd
  nn_distances <- spatstat.geom::nndist(points_ppp)
  nn_mean <- mean(nn_distances)
  nn_expected <- 0.5 / sqrt(points_ppp$n / spatstat.geom::area.owin(spatstat.geom::as.owin(points_ppp)))
  nn_mean / nn_expected # nearest neighbour index
})
df_nni <- data.frame(values = summary.nni, factor = "nni")
paste0(round(mean(summary.nni),2), " (<1 = clustering, >1 = dispersion)")
## [1] "0.43 (<1 = clustering, >1 = dispersion)"

Larval dispersal (sum of squared distances around the mean)

summary.dispersion <- sapply(
  split(output_points, output_points$id),
  function(sub_df) { # Applying function over each split
    mean(calculate_dispersion(sub_df))
  }
)
df_dispersion <- data.frame(values = summary.dispersion, factor = "dispersion")
paste0(round(mean(summary.dispersion),2), " m2")
## [1] "50.5 m2"


Plot outputs

As violin plots:

df_all <- rbind(df_meanproportion, df_meantime, df_meandistance, df_footprint, df_meandensity, df_maxdensity, df_nnd, df_nni, df_dispersion) |> mutate(level = "a")

ggplot() +
  theme_bw() + xlab("") +
  ggtitle("Summary statistics") +
  facet_wrap(~factor, scales = "free") +
  geom_violin(data = df_all, aes(
    x = factor, y = values,
    fill = factor
  ), alpha = 0.8, show.legend = FALSE) +
  ggbeeswarm::geom_quasirandom(
    data = df_all, aes(x = factor, y = values),
    alpha = 0.2, size = 0.2, show.legend = FALSE
  )

or as ridge plots:

ggplot() +
  theme_bw() + ylab("") + xlab("") +
  ggtitle("Summary statistics") +
  facet_wrap(~factor, scales = "free") +
  ggridges::geom_density_ridges2(
    data = df_all,
    aes(x = values, y = 0, fill = factor), alpha = 0.8, show.legend = FALSE
  )

To map settlers and visualise the spatial footprint, use map_coralseed_future:


Map outputs

map_coralseed_future(points=output_points, paths=output_paths, 
              seascape_probability=seascape, restoration.plot=c(100,100))
